Nancy Nord of the Consumer Product Safety Commission condemned the entry of hazardous products into the U.S. market, particularly those for children.
Allmark swiftly recalled tainted toys, urging parents to keep them away from kids.
Mattel apologized for the recall affecting 967,000 toys, anticipating a $30 million income loss.
Concerns arose over toy safety and the industry's self-regulation.
The recall highlighted China's role in product safety issues, with lead paint incidents sparking alarm.
Companies like RC2 and Mattel vowed to enhance safety measures and hold suppliers accountable.
The recall underscored the need for stricter import controls to safeguard consumers.
